  section "Source" {
    url = "https://blog.langchain.com/improving-deep-agents-with-harness-engineering/"
    author = "LangChain"
    date = "2026-02-17"
  }

  section "Context" {
    text = "LangChain improved their coding agent from Top 30 to Top 5 on Terminal Bench 2.0 (+13.7 points) by changing only the harness, not the model. The core insight: 'The purpose of the harness engineer is to prepare and deliver context so agents can autonomously complete work.'"
  }

  section "Key Findings" {
    text = "1. Build-verify loop: Models don't naturally self-verify. The most common failure: agent writes solution, re-reads its own code, confirms it looks ok, stops. Explicit prompting for a plan-build-verify-fix cycle dramatically improved results. A PreCompletionChecklistMiddleware forces verification before exit. 2. Context engineering: Agents struggle with context discovery and search. Injecting directory structure, available tools, and coding practices on start reduces the error surface. Teaching agents their evaluation criteria helps avoid 'slop buildup'. 3. Loop detection: A LoopDetectionMiddleware tracks per-file edit counts and nudges agents to reconsider after N edits to the same file. Design heuristic for today's model limitations. 4. Reasoning budget: More compute on planning and verification, less on implementation ('reasoning sandwich'). Spending max reasoning everywhere caused timeouts. Adaptive allocation outperformed uniform high spend. 5. Trace-driven improvement: An automated Trace Analyzer skill fetches experiment traces, spawns parallel error-analysis agents, synthesizes suggestions. Similar to boosting — focuses on mistakes from previous runs."
  }

  section "Relevance to Mos" {
    text = "Validates Mos's harness-first approach to governance. LangChain's PreCompletionChecklistMiddleware is analogous to Mos's harness run — mechanical verification against defined criteria before work is accepted. Their trace-driven improvement loop parallels Mos's audit command. Their emphasis on 'context engineering on behalf of agents' validates Mos's Console First principle: the CLI is the API. Key insight for Mos: agents benefit enormously from knowing their evaluation criteria upfront. Mos contracts with Gherkin scenarios serve exactly this purpose — they tell the agent what 'done' looks like before work begins."
  }
